SIMPLE: fetch
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fetch
<hw>Fetch</hw> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧ch; 224)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fetched</conjf> 2; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos>. <conjf>Fetching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fecchen</ets>, AS. <ets>feccan</ets>, perh. the same word as
<ets>fetian</ets>; or cf. <ets>facian</ets> to wish to get, OFries.
<ets>faka</ets> to prepare. ⟦root⟧77. Cf. <er>Fet</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bear toward the person speaking, or
the person or thing from whose point of view the action is contemplated;
to go and bring; to get.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Time will run back and <qex>fetch</qex> the age of gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He called to her, and said, <qex>Fetch</qex> me, I pray thee, a
little water in a vessel, that I may drink. And as she was going to
<qex>fetch</qex> it he called to her, and said, Bring me, I pray thee, a
morsel of bread in thine hand.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings xvii. 11,
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To obtain as price or equivalent; to sell
for.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our native horses were held in small esteem, and
<qex>fetched</qex> low prices.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To recall from a swoon; to revive; -- sometimes with
<xex>to</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>fetch</ex> a man to</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fetching</qex> men again when they swoon.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To reduce; to throw.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sudden trip in wrestling that <qex>fetches</qex> a man to the
ground.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To bring to accomplishment; to achieve; to make; to
perform, with certain objects; <as>as, to <ex>fetch</ex> a compass; to
<ex>fetch</ex> a leap; to <ex>fetch</ex> a sigh.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll <qex>fetch</qex> a turn about the garden.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>fetches</qex> his blow quick and sure.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To bring or get within reach by going; to reach; to
arrive at; to attain; to reach by sailing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Meantine flew our ships, and straight we <qex>fetched</qex>⟦br⟧
The siren's isle.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To cause to come; to bring to a particular
state.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They could n't <qex>fetch</qex> the butter in the churn.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Barnes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fetch a compass</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
make a circuit; to take a circuitous route going to a place.</cd> --
<col><b>To fetch a pump</b></col>, <cd>to make it draw water by pouring
water into the top and working the handle.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To
fetch headway</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To fetch
sternway</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to move ahead or
astern.</cd> -- <col><b>To fetch out</b></col>, <cd>to develop.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧The skill of the polisher <xex>fetches out</xex> the colors [of
marble]⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au> -- <col><b>To fetch up</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To overtake.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Says [the
hare], I can <xex>fetch up</xex> the tortoise when I please.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>L'Estrange.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To stop suddenly.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fetch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: fetch
<hw>fetch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To bring one's self; to make
headway; to veer; <as>as, to <ex>fetch</ex> about; to <ex>fetch</ex> to
windward.</as></def> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fetch away</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to break
loose; to roll or slide to leeward.</cd> -- <col><b>To fetch and
carry</b></col>, <cd>to serve obsequiously, like a trained
spaniel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fetch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fetch
<hw>Fetch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stratagem by which a
thing is indirectly brought to pass, or by which one thing seems
intended and another is done; a trick; an artifice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every little <qex>fetch</qex> of wit and criticism.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The apparation of a living person; a
wraith.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The very <qex>fetch</qex> and ghost of Mrs. Gamp.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The unobstructed region of the ocean over which the
wind blows to generate waves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>RH</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>The length of such a
region.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>RH</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fetch candle</b></col>, <cd>a light seen at night,
superstitiously believed to portend a person's death.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fetcher</ent>⟦br⟧
